04047nam a22006255i 9780226453743DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016049358  a9780226453743  a(DE-B1597)523595  a(OCoLC)987910767  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDT543.822b.M35 2017 4aDT543.822b.M35 2018 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a966.520512231 aMcGovern, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Socialist Peace? :bExplaining the Absence of War in an African Country /cMike McGovern. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b13 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Table -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- tTimeline -- tOne. Explaining the Absence of War -- tPart One. Resentment -- tTwo. “Those Who Eat Monkey Will Never Rule over Us” -- tThree. Articulating Betrayal -- tPart Two. War Averted? -- tFour. An Exceptional Case: The Killings in Nuvanuita -- tPart Three. Afterlives -- tInterlude: “I’m not putting my life on the line . . .” -- tFive. The Rhetoric of Counterinsurgency -- tSix. The Symbolic Death of Sékou Touré -- tSeven. The Cinquantenaire and the Dadis Show -- tEight. Conclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the last twenty years, the West African nation of Guinea has exhibited all of the conditions that have led to civil wars in other countries, and Guineans themselves regularly talk about the inevitability of war. Yet the country has narrowly avoided conflict again and again. In A Socialist Peace?, Mike McGovern asks how this is possible, how a nation could beat the odds and evade civil war. Guinea is rich in resources, but its people are some of the poorest in the world. Its political situation is polarized by fiercely competitive ethnic groups. Weapons flow freely through its lands and across its borders. And, finally, it is still recovering from the oppressive regime of Sékou Touré. McGovern argues that while Touré’s reign was hardly peaceful, it was successful—often through highly coercive and violent measures—at establishing a set of durable national dispositions, which have kept the nation at peace. Exploring the ambivalences of contemporary Guineans toward the afterlife of Touré’s reign as well as their abiding sense of socialist solidarity, McGovern sketches the paradoxes that undergird political stability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGuinea - Politics and government - 1958-1984. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGuinea.  aTouré.  acivil war.  acoercion.  aethnicity.  aparadox.  apeace.  asocialism.  asolidarity.  astability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022645357640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226453743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226453743/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles